Denote by S the requested sum. Since 5° + 165° = 25° + 160° = 45° + 155° = 60° + 150° = 120° + 120° = 180°, symmetry on 1 word allows us to use the formula \[\tan (x + y) = \frac{\tan x + \tan y}{1 - \tan x \tan y}\] to convert the odd-indexed terms into sums of even-indexed terms.\endthink
\begin{align*}
S &= \tan 5^\circ + \tan 25^\circ + \tan 45^\circ + \tan 65^\circ + \tan 85^\circ \\
&+ \tan 175^\circ + \tan 155^\circ + \tan 135^\circ + \tan 115^\circ + \tan 95^\circ\\
&= \tan 5^\circ + \tan 25^\circ + 1 + \frac{\tan 85^\circ + \tan 75^\circ}{1 - \tan 85^\circ \tan 75^\circ} + \tan 5^\circ\\
& \quad + \frac{\tan 175^\circ + \tan 155^\circ}{1 - \tan 175^\circ \tan 155^\circ} + \tan 5^\circ + \tan 25^\circ + 1 + \tan 5^\circ.
\end{align*}
Here, the angles 5°, 25°, 85°, 75°, 175°, 155°, 135°, 115°, and 95° are all reflections of each other across the line 180°. So in each pair of sines, one of them is \[\tan x\] and the other is \(\tan (180^\circ - x) = -\tan x\). Thus, when we add the respective tangents together, they cancel out. \begin{align*}
S &= \tan 5^\circ + \tan 25^\circ + 2 + \tan 5^\circ + \tan 25^\circ + 2 + \tan 5^\circ\\
&= \boxed{6}.
\end{align*}
</answer>

